## NON-NEGOTIABLE OPERATING RULES:

### RULE 1 — THE CONCEPT IS THE SITE
Before any wireframe, ask: "What if the concept and the experience were the same thing?"
Bruno didn't design a portfolio then add 3D. He asked: what if the portfolio WAS a world?
Push this question on every brief. The answer is always more interesting than a layout.

### RULE 2 — FIND YOUR ONE SIGNATURE TECHNIQUE
Every output needs one technique that becomes the fingerprint.
Executed everywhere. Unmistakable. Examples:
- Text duplication on hover (RXK)
- Clip-path word reveals synced to audio
- Cursor that physically displaces surrounding elements
- WebGL displacement that responds to cursor velocity (not just position)
- Numbers that glitch before counting up
- Images that only fully resolve when cursor rests on them
Choose one. Commit to it. Make it perfect.

### RULE 3 — MOTION IS PHYSICS, NOT JUST EASING
The difference between good and award-winning is weight.
Good: `ease: power3.out`
Award-winning: objects feel like they have mass, momentum, friction.
Achieve this with: spring physics (not just bezier), overshoot on entries,
lag interpolation on cursor (lerp factor 0.08–0.12), velocity-based effects.

### RULE 4 — SOUND ELEVATES EVERYTHING
Interactive sound design: hover ticks, transition whooshes, ambient textures.
Howler.js for web audio. Always: muted by default, toggle visible.
Use sound as a reward — clicking a project card should feel satisfying.
Subtle = professional. Loud = amateur.

### RULE 5 — THE LOADER IS DESIGNED CONTENT
Never show a bare spinner. The load screen is your first impression.
Use it for: awards display (Lempens), world preview, progress counter,
a single well-set word that creates anticipation.
Target: users want to screenshot the loader.

### RULE 6 — PHYSICS WHEN POSSIBLE
Rapier.js for rigid body simulation. Matter.js for lighter 2D cases.
Even without a full physics world: apply spring physics to UI elements.
Draggable stickers. Cards with tilt+inertia. Elements that bounce off each other.
Physics transforms passive viewing into active participation.

### RULE 7 — COLLABORATION CREDITS ARE PART OF THE WORK
"Design by [Name] / Development by [Name] / WebGL by [Name]"
This is industry standard at the top level. Always plan for credit attribution.
Build systems where designer and developer tokens are cleanly separated.

### RULE 8 — UNAPOLOGETIC DESKTOP-FIRST FOR CREATIVE WORK
Lempens says "Switch to desktop." Bruno's best experience is desktop.
For creative portfolio/agency work: desktop is primary, mobile is graceful degradation.
For product/SaaS: mobile-first always.
Know which mode applies. Don't dilute the desktop experience chasing mobile parity.

### RULE 9 — HSL SYSTEM, OBSIDIAN BIAS
The French creative dev community defaults to dark-first: `#171717`, `#191919`, `#0a0a0a`.
Light mode as a variant, not default on creative projects.
All color in HSL. Single accent. Never two competing accent colors.

### RULE 10 — PERFORMANCE = RESPECT
FCP <0.8s. LCP <1.5s. 60fps on mid-tier hardware.
WebGL: dynamic import, capability check first, fallback always.
Fonts: subset, preload. Images: WebP/AVIF, explicit dimensions.
The site must feel instant before it feels beautiful.

